title: For Sale:  Astra A-100 CAL 9mm **60 DAY LAYAWAY**
postcontent: Astra A-100**LAYAWAY AVAILABLE** Condition Used medium wear and tear Price $275.00**Harvey Special* Inventory # G-16360-1 Manufacturer Astra Model A-100 Caliber .9mm Firearm Type Pistol Barrel 3.75in Fun Fact The Astra A-100 is a Spanish double-action/single-action semi-automaticpistol that was manufactured by Astra-Unceta y Cia SA beginning in 1990. It was distributed in the United States by European American Armory (EAA). The A-100 is also known as the "Panther" as imported into the United States by EAA, and some specimens have this roll-marked on the left of the slide. The A-100 design is a further development of Astra's earlier A-80 and A-90 models. The A-80 was originally patterned after the SIG P220. The A-100 is a recoil-operated, locked breech design with improved Browning-style linkless locking. The lock up is similar to the Browning High Power or CZ-75 with locking lugs on the top of the barrel which mate with lugs in the slide (not with a single lug in the ejection port like a SIG P22X.) The pistol's safety features include a manual decocking lever, firing pin block, and hammer safety. The A-100 lacks a manual safety, but depends entirely on a deliberate pull of its trigger to fire it; in this way it is similar to the SIG P22X series of pistols. The double-action trigger pull is relatively long and heavy, thereby precluding the need for a safety as the probability of an inadvertent discharge is low. The A-100 resembles the SIG P228 and is similar in overall size and dimension, but differs in several respects, the most visible being the location of the take-down/disassembly lever on the right side of the frame (from the shooter's point of view) as compared to the SIG design, in which it is located on the left. The A-100 is also slightly heavier than the SIG, owing to its all-steel construction. Additionally, the A-100's chamber contour as visible when the slide is fully forward is rounded whereas the SIG design is squared. The configuration of the hammer is also different, with the A-100 having a rounded hammer provided with a lanyard hole and the SIG having a more conventional spur hammer. Magazines are not interchangeable between the A-100 and SIG pistols, however many holsters made for the SIG P229/228 fit the A-100 satisfactorily. The various A-series pistols were submitted unsuccessfully as contenders for Spanish military contracts beginning in the 1970s. The Lebanese Forces political party named the A-80, A-90, and A-100 as a few of the many semi-automatic pistols in use by that organization's members.

title: For Sale:  Zastava CZ99 .22LR rifle + scope (unfired)
postcontent:
I bought this rifle recently and haven't even had the chance yet to fire it.  An unexpected expense came up, and now I must sell it.  It's a Zastava CZ99 .22LR bolt-action rifle with a gorgeous walnut stock.  I picked this one out of several on the rack, and it had the best-looking wood by far.  It has a new Cabelas-brand 40mm objective, 3x9 variable power, .22LR rimfire scope ($100 + tax) mounted with high-quality Warne rings ($35 + tax).  This scope was about the same price as a Nikon that I also looked at, but the glass was actually better on this one and I preferred the bullet-drop reticle design on the Cabelas-brand.  What's also nice about Cabelas-brand scopes is that it has a lifetime replacement warranty...if it breaks, you bring it to Cabelas and you'll walk out with a brand new replacement.  
The rifle originally came with a set of open sights, but those were removed upon mounting the scope.  The original sights are included with this rifle, as well as the original box and instruction manual.  Also included are three factory magazines...two 5-round and one 10-round.  The original packaging for the scope and rings is included as well.
I cleaned out the factory grease and relubed the action.  I also made a few passes with a Bore Snake down the barrel.  This rifle is clean, lubed, and ready to shoot.  The bolt action is very smooth and locks up tight.  The scope has been bore-sighted, but not zeroed in yet, as I have not fired the rifle.
I'm asking $400 cash for the entire package.  I prefer to sell, but I'm also willing to consider trades depending on what you have to offer.
